article.description:
The San Antonio Silver Stars outran and outshot
the New York Liberty at times Tuesday night -- just not over the
last eight minutes.
article.headline: Silver Stars struggle in final minutes
article.linkText: Tough defense powers Liberty over Silver Stars
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The San Antonio Silver Stars outran and outshot the New York Liberty at times Tuesday night -- just not over the last eight minutes.

Crystal Robinson scored 18 points and the Liberty held San Antonio to one point over the final 5:29 in a 69-60 victory.

"(Coach Richie Adubato) put his defensive lineup on the floor," said Vickie Johnson, who re-entered the game for the Liberty with 5:50 to play. "Were veterans. We know we need to get stops to win.

"Were still not playing the best basketball we can, but its a start. I think were all on the same page, and thats key to getting where we want to go: the playoffs."

Elena Baranova started in place of Tari Phillips and had 11 points and nine rebounds for New York (11-13). Phillips, who didn't start after breaking an unspecified team rule, had 12 points and 12 rebounds, while reserve Linda Frohlich had a career-high 12 points.

Phillips, who was not available for comment after the game, had her ninth double-double of the season.

San Antonio (9-18) did not have a field goal over the final 8:04 after reserve Sylvia Crawley tied the game at 51. 

Crawley scored 13 points and Adrienne Goodson, Gwen Jackson and Marie Ferdinand each added 10 points for the Stars, who are 3-2 under interim coach Shell Dailey since Candi Harvey was fired July 26.

"They picked up their defense," Dailey said. "Were not a team to back down from anyone. We felt we matched up very well with them. We just missed some opportunities."

The Silver Stars used a 16-4 run to take a 59-53 lead behind Crawleys shooting and Ferdinands fearless driving to the hoop, which resulted in six quick free throws.

But Johnson returned to the lineup to guard Ferdinand and New
York returned to its familiar physical style on offense, pounding
the ball down low to Phillips and Baranova, who each had two
baskets as the Liberty regained the lead, 61-59.

Baranova then hit a 3-pointer and fed inside to Phillips, who
was fouled by Crawley and hit one of two free throws.

Asked if it was her biggest shot of the year, Baranova
downplayed it.

"No," she said, "because its not the finals yet."

After Crawley missed a turnaround jumper at the other end,
Johnson missed a 3-pointer, but Phillips stole a pass from Margo
Dydek, and by the time the Stars could manage a foul, the Liberty
were able to shave almost a full minute off the clock.

"Weve got to spell some of our players for the playoffs," said
Adubato, who played all nine of his available players at least 10
minutes. "V.J. only sat down for 29 seconds, but she got a timeout
in there."
